statement.p:
For a differentiable map T(u,v,w)=(x(u,v,w),y(u,v,w),z(u,v,w)), the Jacobian determinant is
\boxed{ J_T(u,v,w) = \frac{\partial(x,y,z)}{\partial(u,v,w)} = \det \begin{pmatrix} x_u\amp x_v\amp x_w\\ y_u\amp y_v\amp y_w\\ z_u\amp z_v\amp z_w \end{pmatrix}. }
The ordinary local volume scale factor is \boxed{|J_T(u,v,w)|.}

subsection.p:
Cylindrical coordinates are x=r\cos\theta, \qquad y=r\sin\theta, \qquad z=z. The derivative matrix with variables (r,\theta,z) is
\begin{pmatrix} \cos\theta\amp -r\sin\theta\amp 0\\ \sin\theta\amp r\cos\theta\amp 0\\ 0\amp 0\amp 1 \end{pmatrix}.
Its determinant is r. Therefore \boxed{dV=r\,dr\,d\theta\,dz.}

statement.p:
Cylindrical coordinates give 0\le r\le3, \qquad 0\le\theta\le2\pi, \qquad 0\le z\le4. The density is just z, and dV=r\,dr\,d\theta\,dz. Thus
M \amp= \int_0^{2\pi}\int_0^3\int_0^4 z\,r\,dz\,dr\,d\theta \amp= \left[\int_0^{2\pi}d\theta\right]\left[\int_0^3 r\,dr\right]\left[\int_0^4 z\,dz\right] \amp= 2\pi\cdot\frac92\cdot8 \amp= 72\pi.
So \boxed{M=72\pi.}

In spherical coordinates, the ball is 0\le\rho\le2, \qquad 0\le\phi\le\pi, \qquad 0\le\theta\le2\pi. Therefore
M \amp= \int_0^{2\pi}\int_0^\pi\int_0^2 (1+\rho)\rho^2\sin\phi\,d\rho\,d\phi\,d\theta \amp= \left[\int_0^{2\pi}d\theta\right]\left[\int_0^\pi\sin\phi\,d\phi\right]\left[\int_0^2(\rho^2+\rho^3)\,d\rho\right] \amp= 2\pi\cdot2\cdot\left[\frac{\rho^3}{3}+\frac{\rho^4}{4}\right]_0^2 \amp= 4\pi\left(\frac83+4\right) \amp= \frac{80\pi}{3}.
So \boxed{M=\frac{80\pi}{3}.}
